

<html>
<head>
<title>Statistical Inference II Classnote</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=right><font size=-2>[Stat Inf II
classnotes, ISI, Kolkata]
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Density estimation I</h1>




<h3>Introduction</h3>

Suppose we have data

<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub> iid with unknown continuous
density f.
</blockquote>

We want to estimate f. Our estimator will be random function,

<blockquote>
<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>;x),
</blockquote>

where x is the point where the estimated density is being evaluated. Often
we shall not show its dependence on the data explicitly and abbreviate it to
just <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x). 


<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Definition:</b>
   
   Call <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top> <i>unbiased</i> if 
   
   <blockquote>
   E(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)) = f(x) for all f and all x.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Theorem:</b>
   
   If <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x) 
                                              <img src=
                                              "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                              align=top>
                                              
                                               0 for all x, the <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top> cannot be unbiased.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
   <td>
   <b><i>Proof:</i></b> 
   
   Let if possible there exist some <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top> which is both nonnegative and
   unbiased. Consider the the order statistics (o.s.) 
   
   <blockquote>
   X<sub>(1)</sub> 
                   <img src=
                   "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                   align=top>
                   
                    ... 
                        <img src=
                        "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                        align=top>
                        
                         X<sub>(n)</sub>
   </blockquote>
   
   
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise DENS.1:</font></b> 
      
      Show that o.s. is sufficient. 
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   
   Define 
   
   <blockquote>
   <img src="image/ftilde.png" align=top>(x) = E(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x) | o.s.) for all x
   </blockquote>
   
   Notice that by virtue of the last exercise it is indeed a statistic. In
   particular it is a function of the o.s.
   <p>For any a,b define
   
   <blockquote>
   P(a,b) = P(X<sub>1</sub> in (a,b))
   </blockquote>
   
   
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise DENS.2:</font></b> 
      
      Show that
      
      <blockquote>
      <img src="image/intft.png" align=center>
      </blockquote>
      
      is an unbiased estimator of P(a,b) for all a,b.
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   <p>
   Let F<sub>n</sub> be the empirical distribution function. 
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise DENS.3:</font></b> 
      
      Show that 
      
      <blockquote>
      F<sub>n</sub>(b) - F<sub>n</sub>(a)
      </blockquote>
      
      is another unbiased estimator of P(a,b) for all a,b. Show further that
      this estimator is a function of the O.S.
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   So we have two unbiased estimators of P(a,b) for all a,b:
   
   <blockquote>
   F<sub>n</sub>(b)-F<sub>n</sub>(a) and 
   <img src="image/intft.png" align=center>
   </blockquote>
    
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise DENS.4:</font></b> 
      
      Show that O.S. is <i>complete</i> sufficient.
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise DENS.5:</font></b> 
      
      Hence arrive at a contradiction to complete the proof.
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   
   <img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
Other than bias, two other quantities relevant here are variance and
mse. These are defined in the usual way:

<blockquote>
MSE at x = E((<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)-f(x))<sup>2</sup>)<br>
variance at x = var(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x))
</blockquote>


<p>
Note that these involve both the unknown density f and the point x. If we
want to judge the performance of <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top> <i>as a function</i> we define Mean
Integrated Squared Error (MISE) as

<blockquote>
MISE = E(integral of (<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)-f(x))<sup>2</sup>)dx
</blockquote>

We shall not work with MISE in this course. Here are some popular density
estimation techniques:
<ol>
<li>Histogram-like kernel estimator
<li>General kernel estimator
<li>Nearest neighbour/variable width kernel estimators
<li>Spline estimators
</ol>

<h3>Histogram-like kernel estimator</h3>

Let x be the point where we want to estimate f. Then define 

<blockquote>
<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x) = #{X<sub>i</sub>'s with h distance of x}/(2nh)
</blockquote>

Here h is called the bandwidth, and is chosen appropriately (more on this
later). The motivation behind this comes from the fact that

<blockquote>
(F(x+h)-F(x-h))/(2h) 
                     <img src=
                     "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
                     align=middle>
                     
                      f(x),
</blockquote>

as h 
     <img src=
     "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
     align=middle>
     
      0. So we hope that if h is sufficiently small then for
large n the <img src="image/fhat.png" align=top> will be close to f.

<p>How to choose h? We shall choose it so that the MSE is minimised
asymptotically. 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.6:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   Var(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)) = p*(1-p)/(4nh<sup>2</sup>)
   </blockquote>
   
   where p = F(x+h)-F(x-h).
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.7:</font></b> 
   
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   Bias(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)) = p/(2*h)-f(x),
   </blockquote>
   
   where p is as in the last exercise.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.8:</font></b> 
   
   Expand F in Taylor series around x and show that
   
   <blockquote>
   
   p = 2h f(x)+h<sup>3</sup> f<sup>(2)</sup>(x)/3 + higher terms.
   
   </blockquote>
   
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.9:</font></b> 
   
   Hence conclude that bias is of order O(h<sup>2</sup>) and variance is of
   order O&nbsp;(1/nh)
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.10:</font></b> 
   
   Using the last exercise argue that the lowest order of MSE is achieved
   when h = O(n<sup>-1/5</sup>). Also show that this lowest order is 
   O(n<sup>-4/5</sup>).
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   



<h3>Kernel density estimation</h3>

Let K be a density function symmetric around 0, e.g., N(0,1) density. Then
check that 

<blockquote>
K(x; a, h) := K((x-a)/h)/h
</blockquote>

is also a valid density for any a in R and any h &gt; 0. K(.;a,h) is a
shifted-scaled version of K. We call K as our kernel. We define the kernel
density estimator using this kernel as

<blockquote>
<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(a) = 
                                          <img src=
                                          "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
                                          align=middle>
                                          
                                           K(X<sub>i</sub>; a, h)/n.
</blockquote>


<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.11:</font></b> 
   
   Show that for a particular choice of K, we get the histogram type
   estimator that we discussed earlier. 
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.12:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   Var(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)) = O(1/(nh))
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.13:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   Bias(<img src="image/fhat.png" align=top>(x)) = O(h<sup>2</sup>)
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Hence the best choice for h is again O(n<sup>-1/5</sup>).
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise DENS.14:</font></b> 
   
   Suggest a method to simulate from kernel density estimate.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


